"# Chapter 1: The Surface (of Sound)

*Core concept: `(audio/play 'tone freq dur)` — a bare sine at a chosen frequency*
*Material: pure tones*
*Finale artifact: A tone that rings*

**A note on the code you're about to read (added 2026-07-18):**

Every code example in this chapter uses `(audio/play 'tone freq dur)` — the canonical CORE form for playing a single sine wave. Older printings of this chapter used a bare `(tone freq dur)` shorthand; those calls have been rewritten to the CORE form. The prose still refers to `(tone freq dur)` in some sentences because it reads more like a music textbook that way — think of `tone` as the short English name for the operation, and `(audio/play 'tone ...)` as the actual Scheme call the runtime evaluates. Both mean the same thing; only the second one runs.

If you're following along in the REPL, always type the `(audio/play 'tone ...)` form.

---

## 1.1 The Honest Beginning

We call it *music*, but we are really dealing with **sound** — vibrations in the air that reach your ear, modeled as waves that reach a speaker. This book will teach you to make sound from scratch, shape it into melody and rhythm, and eventually conduct a full Romantic piano concerto. But we start where sound itself starts: with a single, pure tone.

You do not need to know anything about programming or music notation to begin. This chapter teaches both from zero. By the end, you will have written small programs that make tones ring, and you will understand what those programs *mean* — not just what they *do*.

**What you will learn:**

- How to make a tone at a chosen frequency and duration.
- The three simplest sound-making verbs: `beep`, `tone`, and `chime`.
- How to name things and call them back.
- How sound is measured: frequency in Hertz, duration in beats.

**What you will make:**

A tone that rings — a single sine wave you can hear, whose pitch and length you chose.

---

## 1.2 The Sine Wave — The Simplest Sound

All sound is vibration. A *sine wave* is the simplest vibration: a smooth, repeating curve with no edges, no texture, no color — just one pure frequency. When you hear a sine wave, it sounds clean, glassy, almost unnatural, because most sounds in the world are richer mixtures. But the sine is the building block. Everything else is made by combining sines.

[VISUAL: A sine wave plotted over time — one smooth cycle, labeled \"One cycle = one period = 1/frequency seconds\"]

The **frequency** of a sine wave is how many times per second it repeats — measured in **Hertz (Hz)**. A tone at 440 Hz vibrates 440 times per second. That frequency corresponds to the musical pitch **A4** (the A above middle C on a piano).

The **duration** is how long the tone sounds. For now, we measure duration in **seconds**, but later (starting in Chapter 3) we will shift to *musical time* — beats and measures — because that is how music is structured.

The **amplitude** is how loud the wave is. We will not control amplitude directly yet; the engine sets a reasonable default. (Loudness is taught properly in Chapter 13, when we discuss dynamics.)

---

## 1.3 Your First Program: `(beep)`

Here is the simplest sound program you can write in Motoi Scheme:

```scheme
(beep)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (beep) to emit a short blip tone through the audio engine, ~440 Hz, ~0.15s duration -->

That is a complete program. When you run it, it makes a short blip — a beep. The program is *one form*: a list with one word inside parentheses. In Scheme, parentheses mean \"do this thing.\" The word `beep` is a **verb** — a built-in command the system knows how to execute.

Try it now. Type that line into the runtime REPL (the interactive prompt where you run Scheme code) and press Enter. You will hear a small sound.

**What just happened:**

1. The system read the form `(beep)`.
2. It recognized `beep` as a known verb.
3. It told the audio engine, \"make a short tone.\"
4. The speaker vibrated, and you heard it.

This is the fundamental loop of all programming: you write a form, the system evaluates it, something happens in the world.

---

## 1.4 A Tone of Your Own: `(tone freq dur)`

The `beep` is fixed — it always makes the same pitch for the same brief moment. To make *your own* tone — a pitch you choose, lasting as long as you decide — use the `tone` verb:

```scheme
(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (tone freq dur) to emit a sine wave at freq Hz for dur seconds -->

This form has *three* parts:

- `tone` — the verb (what to do).
- `440` — the first argument (the frequency, in Hz).
- `1.0` — the second argument (the duration, in seconds).

Run that program. You will hear a pure A4 tone that lasts for one second.

**Try these:**

```scheme
(audio/play 'tone 220 0.5)   ; A3 (one octave lower), half a second
```

```scheme
(audio/play 'tone 880 2.0)   ; A5 (one octave higher), two seconds
```

```scheme
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 1.5)  ; Middle C (C4), one and a half seconds
```

Each of those is a complete program. Each makes a single sine wave. The frequency controls the *pitch* (how high or low it sounds). The duration controls how long it rings.

**Frequency and pitch:**

Doubling the frequency raises the pitch by one **octave** (the same note name, one register higher). Halving it lowers the pitch by one octave. The mapping between frequency and musical pitch is precise and worth learning, but for now, just know:

- **Middle C (C4):** ~261.63 Hz
- **A4 (concert A):** 440 Hz
- **A5:** 880 Hz
- **A3:** 220 Hz

(Chapter 3 will introduce `note`, which lets you write pitches by name — `C4`, `A4` — instead of raw frequency numbers. But `tone` is more honest: it shows you that pitch *is* frequency.)

---

## 1.5 A Small Flourish: `(chime)`

The third sound verb you have today is `chime`:

```scheme
(chime)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire (chime) to emit a small 3-note arpeggio, ascending, pleasant default pitches, ~0.6s total -->

Run that. You will hear a small, pleasant arpeggio — three notes in quick succession, rising. This is still made of sine waves (three of them, played one after another), but it feels more musical than a single tone. It is your first *sequence* — multiple sounds in time.

The `chime` is fixed, like `beep`. You cannot yet choose which notes it plays. (That control will come when we introduce `note` and lists in Chapter 3.) But it is already more than one sound, and that is the direction we are heading: from one tone to many, from isolated pitches to phrases, from bare sines to shaped voices.

---

## 1.6 Naming Things: `define`

You have made tones. Now let us **name** them, so we can call them back without retyping the numbers every time.

In Scheme, you name things with `define`:

```scheme
(define concert-a (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0))
```

This form does two things:

1. It evaluates `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)` — makes a 440 Hz tone for 1 second.
2. It binds the *name* `concert-a` to that action, so you can invoke it later.

Now, whenever you write `concert-a` (without parentheses, just the name), the system knows you mean \"that A4 tone.\" But to *execute* it — to actually make the sound — you write:

```scheme
concert-a
```

Wait. That did nothing, because `concert-a` is bound to the *result* of evaluating `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)`, which already happened when you defined it. The sound played *once*, when the definition ran. If you want a **reusable sound** — something you can call over and over — you need a **function**. We will teach that in Section 1.7.

For now, understand: `define` names a value. If that value is the result of calling `tone`, the tone plays when the definition runs, and the name holds whatever `tone` returned (likely nothing audible — the sound already happened). To make a **callable sound**, we need one more idea.

---

## 1.7 Making a Callable Sound: `lambda`

A **lambda** is an unnamed function — a little machine that does something when you call it. Here is a lambda that makes a tone:

```scheme
(lambda () (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0))
```

That form means: \"a function that takes no arguments, and when called, executes `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)`.\"

You can call it immediately by wrapping it in parentheses with an empty argument list:

```scheme
((lambda () (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)))
```

<!-- BUILD: ensure lambda forms evaluate correctly; calling a lambda with () invokes its body -->

Run that. You will hear the A4 tone.

But more usefully, you can **name** the lambda, so you can call it whenever you want:

```scheme
(define ring-a
  (lambda () (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)))
```

Now `ring-a` is a **callable sound**. Every time you write:

```scheme
(ring-a)
```

…you hear the tone. The parentheses mean \"call this function.\" The function, when called, executes `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)`, and the tone sounds.

**Why does this matter?**

Because now you can build a *vocabulary* of sounds — named, reusable fragments — and combine them. Let us make a few:

```scheme
(define ring-a
  (lambda () (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)))

(define ring-c
  (lambda () (audio/play 'tone 261.63 1.0)))

(define ring-e
  (lambda () (audio/play 'tone 329.63 1.0)))
```

Now you can call them in sequence:

```scheme
(ring-c)
(ring-e)
(ring-a)
```

Run those three lines (as one program, or one at a time). You will hear C, then E, then A — three tones, one after another. That is a **melody fragment**. You just wrote your first phrase.

(Note: the tones will overlap if the system schedules them immediately without waiting for the prior tone to finish. Chapter 5 will introduce the *transport* and precise beat-timing so phrases do not pile up. For now, accept that the tones sound in order, even if they blur together.)

---

## 1.8 Arguments: Making Sounds Flexible

The three `ring-` functions are nice, but each one is locked to a single pitch. What if we want a function that can make *any* tone, at *any* frequency and duration we choose when we call it?

Give the lambda **parameters**:

```scheme
(define make-tone
  (lambda (freq dur)
    (audio/play 'tone freq dur)))
```

Now `make-tone` is a function that takes *two arguments*: a frequency and a duration. When you call it, you supply those values:

```scheme
(make-tone 440 1.0)    ; A4, 1 second
```

```scheme
(make-tone 523.25 0.5) ; C5, half a second
```

```scheme
(make-tone 196.00 2.0) ; G3, 2 seconds
```

Each call makes a different tone, because you passed different arguments. The function is **general** — it works for any frequency and duration you give it.

**This is the pattern you will use everywhere in this book:**

1. Write a `lambda` that takes parameters.
2. Use those parameters in the body to do something (make a tone, play a note, draw a shape).
3. `define` the lambda under a meaningful name.
4. Call the function with specific arguments to get specific results.

---

## 1.9 Putting It Together: A Ringing Tone

Let us write a small program that demonstrates everything you have learned. We will define a function that makes a tone at a given frequency, then call it a few times to create a small ascending sequence:

```scheme
(define ring
  (lambda (freq)
    (audio/play 'tone freq 0.8)))

(ring 261.63)  ; C4
(ring 293.66)  ; D4
(ring 329.63)  ; E4
(ring 349.23)  ; F4
(ring 392.00)  ; G4
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; define ring, call it 5 times with different freqs; ensure each tone sounds for 0.8s -->

Run that program as a whole. You will hear a five-note ascending scale: C–D–E–F–G. Each tone lasts 0.8 seconds. The tones may overlap slightly (again, precise sequencing comes in Chapter 5), but you will hear the rising contour clearly.

**What this program does:**

- Defines `ring`, a function that takes one argument (`freq`) and plays a 0.8-second tone at that frequency.
- Calls `ring` five times, each time with a different frequency corresponding to a note in the C major scale.

**This is your first melody.** It is not written in musical notation yet (Chapter 3 will introduce `note` and staff rendering), and it is not rhythmically precise (Chapter 5 will add the transport and beat-timing), but it is *already music* — a sequence of pitches that move in a meaningful direction.

---

## 1.10 The Chapter Finale: A Tone That Rings

Here is the finale artifact for this chapter — a single, deliberate tone that you shape and name:

```scheme
(define my-tone
  (lambda ()
    (audio/play 'tone 440 2.0)))

(my-tone)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; define my-tone as a no-arg lambda calling (audio/play 'tone 440 2.0), then invoke it -->

Run it. You will hear a pure A4 sine wave that lasts for two full seconds — long enough to feel like it *rings*, not just blips. That is the artifact: **a tone that rings**, made by you, from a program you wrote and understand.

[VISUAL: A sine wave plotted over 2 seconds at 440 Hz, with amplitude on the Y axis and time on the X axis, labeled \"440 Hz (A4), 2.0 seconds — a tone that rings\"]

---

## 1.11 What You Learned

You started this chapter knowing nothing about sound or Scheme. Now you know:

- **Sound is vibration.** A sine wave is the simplest sound — one pure frequency.
- **Frequency is pitch.** Measured in Hertz (Hz); doubling the frequency raises the pitch one octave.
- **Duration is time.** Measured in seconds for now; beats and measures come later.
- **Three sound verbs:** `beep`, `tone`, and `chime`.
- **Two Scheme forms:** `define` (to name things) and `lambda` (to make functions).
- **How to call a function:** wrap it in parentheses with arguments (if it takes any).

You made a tone. You named it. You called it back. You wrote a five-note melody. You built the foundation for everything that follows.

---

## 1.12 What Comes Next

Chapter 2 will teach you the rest of the Scheme foundation you need: lists, `let`, `map`, and **macros** — the forms that let you build larger structures and abstractions. Chapter 3 will introduce `note` (so you can write pitches by name, not raw frequency), the noises soundboard, drums, and your first complete piece: **Twinkle Twinkle Little Star on piano** — the end of the beginning.

But first, a few questions to check your understanding.

---

## End-of-Chapter Questions

1. **What is a sine wave, and why is it called the \"simplest sound\"?**

2. **What is the difference between `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)` and `(define my-tone (lambda () (audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)))`? Which one can you call multiple times?**

3. **Write a program that plays three tones in descending order: G4 (392 Hz), E4 (329.63 Hz), C4 (261.63 Hz). Each tone should last 1 second.**

4. **Define a function called `short-beep` that takes a frequency as an argument and plays a tone at that frequency for 0.3 seconds. Then call it with 523.25 Hz (C5).**

5. **What does \"frequency\" measure, and what unit is it measured in?**

6. **Why do we use `lambda` instead of just writing `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)` directly every time we want that sound?**

---

*End of Chapter 1. Save your work. The next chapter builds on these ideas — you will need them.*


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The Vibrating World

You already know a bare sine tone — `(audio/play 'tone 440 1.0)` — makes a single frequency ring for a duration. You've used `(beep)` to make a quick blip. This refill explores *what else* lives in that same simple space: **different frequencies, different durations, different relationships between them.**

Sound is air molecules bumping into each other. When something vibrates — a guitar string, a tuning fork, your vocal cords, or a speaker cone — it pushes air, and those pushes travel outward as a wave. Your ear turns those pushes back into nerve signals, and your brain calls the result \"sound.\"

**A pure tone is the simplest possible vibration:** a sine wave, one frequency, no overtones, no texture. It's the atom of sound. Everything else — a piano, a voice, a thunderclap — is built from combinations of these atoms, layered and shaped.

We're starting with the atoms.

---


### Frequency Space

Frequency is measured in **Hertz (Hz)** — cycles per second. Middle C on a piano is 261.63 Hz; the A above it (the note orchestras tune to) is 440 Hz. Double the frequency, and you move up one **octave** — the same pitch-name, one register higher.

```scheme
;; A sequence of octaves: A220, A440, A880
(audio/play 'tone 220 0.5)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)
(audio/play 'tone 880 0.5)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; plays three A notes, one octave apart -->`

[VISUAL: A waveform diagram showing three sine waves — the 880 Hz wave has twice as many cycles in the same window as the 440 Hz wave, and 440 has twice as many as 220. Label each with its frequency.]

**What you hear:** The pitch rises, but the *relationship* between each step is the same — each note is twice the frequency of the one before. Your ear hears that doubling as \"the same note, higher.\"

---


### Duration as a Dimension

Duration controls how long the tone sounds. So far you've used whole-second values (`1.0`, `0.5`). But sound time is continuous — you can make a tone last *any* fraction of a second.

```scheme
;; A descending cascade: same pitch, shrinking durations
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 1.0)   ;; C5, whole second
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.5)   ;; half second
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.25)  ;; quarter second
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.125) ;; eighth second
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; same pitch, four different durations -->`

**What you hear:** The same pitch, but each repetition is shorter. The first rings; the last is a quick tap.

---


### Silence is Part of the Surface

The space *between* sounds is as important as the sounds themselves. You can't hear silence directly, but you perceive it as **rest** — the absence of vibration.

In code, silence is just… waiting. You don't need a verb for it; the runtime schedules sounds in sequence, and the gap between two `(tone …)` calls is the rest.

```scheme
;; A tone, a rest, another tone
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.3)
;; (0.5 seconds of implicit silence here because the next tone starts 0.5 sec after this one ends is NOT true — they happen immediately in sequence.)
;; To make a rest, we need to account for it in DURATION or scheduling. For now, just know: if you want a gap, you code it.
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.3)
```

*(Actual rest-timing requires beat-based scheduling, which we'll meet in Chapter 5. For now, recognize that silence is data: a duration with no sounding event.)*

---


### Building Intervals by Ratio

Two tones sounding in sequence make a **melodic interval**; two sounding at the same time make a **harmonic interval**. The *size* of the interval is the ratio between the frequencies.

| Interval name | Ratio | Example (from A440) |
|---------------|-------|---------------------|
| Octave        | 2:1   | 440 → 880 Hz        |
| Perfect fifth | 3:2   | 440 → 660 Hz        |
| Perfect fourth| 4:3   | 440 → 586.67 Hz     |
| Major third   | 5:4   | 440 → 550 Hz        |

```scheme
;; A440 and its perfect fifth (660 Hz), in sequence
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.4)
(audio/play 'tone 660 0.4)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; melodic perfect fifth -->`

```scheme
;; The same fifth, but both frequencies calculated from a base
(let ((base 440))
  (audio/play 'tone base 0.4)
  (audio/play 'tone (* base 1.5) 0.4))  ;; 3:2 ratio = multiply by 1.5
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; demonstrates ratio calculation -->`

[VISUAL: A frequency-ratio diagram showing 440 Hz and 660 Hz as two sine waves, with the 3:2 ratio labeled.]

**Why ratios matter:** Your ear hears frequency relationships, not absolute numbers. A perfect fifth sounds \"the same\" whether it's 220→330 Hz or 440→660 Hz, because the ratio (3:2) is identical.

---


### Sweeping Through Frequency

What if you wanted to play *every* frequency in a range, not just isolated notes?

```scheme
;; A rising sweep: 200 Hz to 800 Hz in 50 Hz steps
(audio/play 'tone 200 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 250 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 300 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 350 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 400 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 450 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 500 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 550 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 600 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 650 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 700 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 750 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 800 0.1)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; chromatic-ish sweep, 13 discrete steps -->`

**What you hear:** A staircase of pitches, each 50 Hz higher than the last. It's not smooth (that would require *continuous* frequency change, a glissando — something we'll meet in Chapter 12*[needs: GAP-2]*), but it's a *scan* of frequency space.

---


### The Sub-Bass and the Dog Whistle

Human hearing spans roughly **20 Hz to 20,000 Hz** (20 kHz). Below 20 Hz, you feel vibration more than you hear pitch. Above 20 kHz, most adults hear nothing (though children and some animals can).

```scheme
;; A sub-bass tone: 40 Hz, right at the edge of hearing
(audio/play 'tone 40 1.0)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; very low frequency -->`

**What you hear (or feel):** A low rumble. If your speakers or headphones can't reproduce 40 Hz, you might hear almost nothing — the tone is real, but your playback device is the bottleneck.

```scheme
;; A very high tone: 8000 Hz (8 kHz), well within hearing but piercing
(audio/play 'tone 8000 0.3)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; high frequency -->`

**What you hear:** A sharp, thin whistle. It's uncomfortable if too loud — high frequencies are perceived as \"brighter\" and more attention-grabbing.

*(Tones above 15 kHz are outside the book's scope — we're teaching music, and musical pitches live in the 20 Hz – ~4 kHz range for fundamentals, with overtones extending higher.)*

---


### Repetition and Pattern

Sound in time is pattern. Even the simplest pattern — the same tone, repeated — creates a **rhythm**.

```scheme
;; A steady pulse: 440 Hz, eight repetitions, 0.2 sec each
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; eight-beat pulse -->`

**What you hear:** A metronomic tick. If you count along, you're perceiving the pattern as a beat.

---


### Two Frequencies, Two Durations

Now combine what you know: different frequencies *and* different durations in the same sequence.

```scheme
;; A two-note motif: short low, long high
(audio/play 'tone 220 0.15)   ;; short A3
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.6)    ;; long A4
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; simple two-note gesture -->`

**What you hear:** A short low note \"leads into\" a longer high note. This is a **melodic gesture** — the simplest kind of musical shape.

---


### Three Tones, Three Durations

```scheme
;; A three-note descent: long, medium, short
(audio/play 'tone 660 0.5)    ;; E5
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.3) ;; C5
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.15)   ;; A4
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; descending three-note figure -->`

**What you hear:** A falling line. The durations shrink as the pitch falls, so the gesture *accelerates* — it feels like it's \"landing.\"

---


### Alternating High and Low

```scheme
;; A four-note alternation: high, low, high, low
(audio/play 'tone 880 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 880 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; octave alternation -->`

**What you hear:** A bouncing pattern. The octave leap (2:1 ratio) makes the high and low feel like \"the same note\" in different registers.

---


### Five Steps Ascending

```scheme
;; A five-note rising scale fragment
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.25)  ;; C4
(audio/play 'tone 293.66 0.25)  ;; D4
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.25)  ;; E4
(audio/play 'tone 349.23 0.25)  ;; F4
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.25)  ;; G4
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; five-note major scale -->`

**What you hear:** The start of a major scale. You recognize it even though we haven't taught \"scales\" yet — your ear knows this pattern from a lifetime of listening.

---


### The Unison

Two tones at the *same* frequency make a **unison** — not an interval, but a reinforcement.

```scheme
;; Two 440 Hz tones, one right after the other
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.4)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.4)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; repeated unison -->`

**What you hear:** The same pitch, twice. In melody, unison repetition is emphasis.

---


### Octave Doubling

```scheme
;; A note and its octave, in sequence
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.4)  ;; C4
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.4)  ;; C5 (one octave up)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; octave leap -->`

**What you hear:** The second note sounds \"like the first, but higher.\" Octaves are the most consonant interval — so consonant that many cultures hear them as \"the same note.\"

---


### A Falling Fourth

```scheme
;; A perfect fourth, descending
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.35) ;; C5
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.35) ;; G4 (4:3 ratio down = multiply by 3/4)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; descending fourth -->`

[VISUAL: A frequency diagram showing 523.25 Hz and 392 Hz, labeled with the 4:3 ratio.]

---


### The Major Third

```scheme
;; A major third: C to E
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.3)  ;; C4
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.3)  ;; E4 (5:4 ratio)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; major third interval -->`

**What you hear:** A bright, open interval. Major thirds sound \"happy\" to Western-trained ears — that's cultural conditioning, but the 5:4 ratio is mathematically simple, so it feels stable.

---


### A Sequence of Thirds

```scheme
;; Three major thirds in a row
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.25) ;; C
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.25) ;; E
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.25) ;; G
(audio/play 'tone 493.88 0.25) ;; B
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; chain of thirds -->`

**What you hear:** A rising arpeggio. You're sketching a chord (C major seventh) in time, one note at a time.

---


### Long and Short

```scheme
;; A rhythm pattern: long, short, short, long
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.6)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.6)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; rhythmic variation on a single pitch -->`

**What you hear:** Rhythm is pattern *in time*. Even on a single pitch, duration creates shape.

---


### A Seven-Note Figure

```scheme
;; A seven-note melodic shape
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.2)  ;; G4
(audio/play 'tone 440.00 0.2)  ;; A4
(audio/play 'tone 493.88 0.2)  ;; B4
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.2)  ;; C5
(audio/play 'tone 493.88 0.2)  ;; B4
(audio/play 'tone 440.00 0.2)  ;; A4
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.4)  ;; G4 (longer, so it \"lands\")
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; seven-note arch -->`

**What you hear:** A rising and falling arc. The last note is longer, so it feels like a conclusion.

---


### Calculating Frequencies from a Base

Instead of hardcoding frequencies, calculate them from a starting pitch.

```scheme
;; A major scale, calculated from C4 (261.63 Hz)
(let ((c 261.63))
  (audio/play 'tone c 0.25)                        ;; C
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.122462) 0.25)           ;; D (multiply by 2^(2/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.259921) 0.25)           ;; E (2^(4/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.334840) 0.25)           ;; F (2^(5/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.498307) 0.25)           ;; G (2^(7/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.681793) 0.25)           ;; A (2^(9/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 1.887749) 0.25)           ;; B (2^(11/12))
  (audio/play 'tone (* c 2.0) 0.25))               ;; C (octave)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; equal-tempered major scale from calculated ratios -->`

**What's happening:** Each note in the equal-tempered scale is 2^(n/12) times the base frequency, where n is the number of semitones up. (We'll teach temperament and tuning systems properly in Chapter 7; for now, just recognize that the math produces the pitches.)

---


### A Rhythmic Motif

```scheme
;; Short-short-long, repeated twice
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.45)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.15)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.45)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; rhythmic motif, single pitch -->`

**What you hear:** A rhythmic cell. This is the same shape you'd hear in Morse code (· · —), or the opening of Beethoven's Fifth (·  · · —). Rhythm is pattern, and pattern is information.

