### A Falling Glissando (Stepped)

A true glissando is a *continuous* frequency sweep, which requires engine support we don't have yet*[needs: GAP-2]*. But you can approximate it with small discrete steps.

```scheme
;; A stepped \"glissando\" from 800 Hz to 400 Hz in 20 Hz steps
(audio/play 'tone 800 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 780 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 760 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 740 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 720 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 700 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 680 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 660 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 640 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 620 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 600 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 580 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 560 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 540 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 520 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 500 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 480 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 460 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 420 0.05)
(audio/play 'tone 400 0.05)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; stepped frequency descent -->`

**What you hear:** A descending sweep. It's not smooth (each step is audible), but it's much closer to a glissando than a simple two-note drop.

