### A Bouncing Ball (Pitch)

Imagine a ball bouncing and losing energy — the bounces get closer together in time *and* lower in pitch.

```scheme
;; A \"bouncing\" melodic pattern: descending, accelerating
(audio/play 'tone 523.25 0.4)   ;; C5
(audio/play 'tone 440.00 0.3)   ;; A4
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.2)   ;; G4
(audio/play 'tone 349.23 0.15)  ;; F4
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.1)   ;; E4
(audio/play 'tone 311.13 0.08)  ;; D♯4
(audio/play 'tone 293.66 0.06)  ;; D4
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; bouncing decay pattern -->`

**What you hear:** A decaying bounce. The pitches descend and the durations shrink, so it sounds like it's \"settling.\"

---


### The Fibonacci Sequence (as Durations)

The Fibonacci sequence (1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, …) appears in nature and art. Use it as a duration pattern.

```scheme
;; Fibonacci durations (scaled to tenths of a second): 0.1, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.5, 0.8
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.3)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.8)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; Fibonacci duration pattern -->`

**What you hear:** Each note is longer than the sum of the two before it. The rhythm expands organically.

---


### A Six-Note Whole-Tone Scale

The **whole-tone scale** divides the octave into six equal whole steps. It has no semitones, so it sounds \"floating\" and unresolved.

```scheme
;; Whole-tone scale from C: C D E F♯ G♯ A♯
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.25)  ;; C
(audio/play 'tone 293.66 0.25)  ;; D
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.25)  ;; E
(audio/play 'tone 369.99 0.25)  ;; F♯
(audio/play 'tone 415.30 0.25)  ;; G♯
(audio/play 'tone 466.16 0.25)  ;; A♯
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; whole-tone scale -->`

**What you hear:** A dreamy, ambiguous scale. Debussy loved this sound.

---


### A Syncopated Rhythm

**Syncopation** is emphasis on the weak beats or off-beats. Here's a rhythm where the longer notes fall *between* the expected strong beats.

```scheme
;; Syncopated pattern: short, LONG, short, LONG, short
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.4)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.1)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.4)
(audio/play 'tone 330 0.1)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; syncopated rhythm, single pitch -->`

**What you hear:** The accents fall in unexpected places. Your ear wants to latch onto the long notes as \"beats,\" but they're offset.

---


### A Descending Sequence

A **sequence** is a musical pattern repeated at a different pitch level.

```scheme
;; A three-note motif, repeated a step lower, then another step lower
;; Motif 1: E F G
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 349.23 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 392.00 0.3)
;; Motif 2: D E F (same shape, one step down)
(audio/play 'tone 293.66 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 349.23 0.3)
;; Motif 3: C D E (same shape, another step down)
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 293.66 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 329.63 0.3)
```
`<!-- BUILD: runnable standalone; descending sequence -->`

**What you hear:** The same melodic gesture, falling in pitch. Sequences are one of the most common ways to develop a musical idea.

---


